    </table>
    </center></div><p align="left"><font face="Arial" color="#C1C1FF"><strong><a name="Darkstone goodness">Darkstone goodness</a></strong></font><a href="mailto:sacrates@voodooextreme.com"><small> - Sacrates</small></a><br>
    <small>Ah, just after we got that fuzzy goodness from the chimps working on Darkstone,
    looks like the console lovin Ho's over at Next Gen have slipped up a nice little Preview.
    Check it.</small></p>
    <blockquote>
      <font color="#ffffff" face="Arial" size="2"><p></font><font color="#8080C0" face="Bookman Old Style" size="2">Darkstone is a fine looking 3D game from Take 2 that has
      the overhead RPG style of Diablo, with the weapons, spells, and NPCs to interact with. But
      the game also has the fully realized 3D environment of Myth, with the camera spinning and
      the zooming in and out. The difference being that the characters here are fully polygonal,
      not sprites</font></p>
    </blockquote>
    <p align="center"><font color="#C1C1FF" face="Tempus Sans ITC"><strong><small>&nbsp;</small></strong></font></p>
    <p align="center"><font color="#C1C1FF" face="Tempus Sans ITC"><strong><small>&nbsp;</small></strong></font></p>
    <div align="center"><center><table border="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%" bgcolor="#660066" bordercolor="#FFBBFF">
      <tr>
        <td width="100%"><small><strong>Friday November 20, 1998 </strong><small><font color="#C0C0C0">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; EQ Fast Day Eight: Step into
        the light...</font></small></small></td>
      </tr>
    </table>
    </center></div><p align="left"><font face="Arial" color="#C1C1FF"><strong><a name="How big is ME?">How big is ME?</a></strong></font><a href="mailto:sacrates@voodooextreme.com"><small> - Sacrates</small></a><br>
    <small>Now here is an interesting question that our Ho boy Stephen Nichols jumped on.
    Pretty much says <font color="#FFFFFF"><strong>who's got the bigger</strong></font>..uh...World.</small></p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><small><font color="#8080C0" face="Bookman Old Style">Origin touts UO's map to be
      &quot;nearly 200 million square feet of stunning 3-D terrain&quot;. Now, assuming that
      those &quot;square feet&quot; are in game-space, we can do a little math. If the map is
      sqare in shape then it must be 14,142 feet across. That would put it at 2.6 miles across.
      Now, if you had a walker or a cane it might take you 7 hours to cross that distance.
      Otherwise, I'd put it at an hour on foot.</font></small></p>
      <p><small><font color="#8080C0" face="Bookman Old Style">Our map is 20,000 surface rooms
      (not counting the HUGE underground areas, like Moria) each one of those rooms is 3200
      pixels square. Our male human character is 140 pixels tall and stands about 6 feet in game
      space. That puts the number of game-space feet to cross a room at 139. That means that
      each room is 19,321 square feet. Take that and multiply it by 20,000 and you get
      386,420,000 in surface area alone (I'm estimating another 100,000,000 square feet in
      subterranean areas). Using that math, you can determine that you would come across another
      player every 38,642 feet of travel which is about 1 other player for every 1.75 rooms you
      cross. That, of course, assumes perfect distribution. There will be areas of
      concentration, but without teleportation it will be extremely difficult for very large
      concentrations to exist. This also assumes that 10,000 people are online. I would imagine
      that 30 percent of the population would be underground, so that further relieves the
      potential crowding problem. </font></small></p>
      <p><small><font color="#8080C0" face="Bookman Old Style">It will take you a little over an
      hour on foot to cross our map if you could go in a straight line and were not interrupted
      (which is not likely). Having a horse will help. I think this is large enough for a game.
      Certainly, the real Middle-earth was much larger but there has to be a balance between
      size and playability. Not to mention that it would take MANY CDs to hold a map that was
      the &quot;correct&quot; scale.</font></small></p>
      <p><small><font color="#8080C0" face="Bookman Old Style">I hope this answers your
      question.</font></small></p>
    </blockquote>
