    <p align="left"><font face="Arial" color="#C1C1FF"><strong><a name="Even More BG Lovin">Even
    More BG Lovin</a> </strong></font><a href="mailto:rbowmaster@shaw.wave.ca"><small>-
    Bowmeister</small></a><br>
    <small>Wow...Greg Peterson has been <font color="#FFFFFF"><strong>burning up the bandwidth</strong></font>
    over on the Backroom message boards. First off is a big post on strategies for the makeup
    of characters within your party...</small></p>
    <blockquote>
      <p align="left"><small><font color="#8080C0" face="Bookman Old Style">Thought I'd
      jump-start some new discussion here cuz everyone is starting to get fried listening to
      un-ending release date and beta testing posts.<br>
      <br>
      I have been reading a LOT of posts about the 'ultimate' character class combination.
      Having played both AD&amp;D and BG I think people need to shift their gears a little.
      AD&amp;D is all about PARTY based adventuring. It is the same with BG. Instead of focusing
      on the ultimate single character, people should be thinking about the ultimate party --
      and then start recruiting players to fill those roles. Put differently, in UO everyone
      talks about 'tank mages' as being the most powerful character to play. In BG I think
      people are taking the tank mage thing and are applying it to a Fighter/Mage and thinking
      that that is the all around best combination (good melee power, good strategic spell use).
      However, a party of 4 fighters &amp; 2 mages will ALWAYS (IMHO) be able to to take out 6
      fighter/mages of the same experience point level...<br>
      <br>
      For example, assuming all characters have 65,000 xp, you would have four 7th level
      fighters (with their extra attacks) and two 7th level mages (with 4th level spells)
      against 6 6th/5th level Fighter/Mages (with standard attacks and 3rd level spells). If
      those 7th level fighters are dwarves (with high constitution and innate magic resistance)
      the balance can become even be more skewed.<br>
      <br>
      Granted, there are exceptions to every rule and you could always get lucky... in the above
      example you could always come upon the party of 7th level characters, surprise them, and
      IF they were in a small area, and IF none of your characters were wearing armor you could
      fire off 6 fireballs and probably take out most of them... (average damage 6 level 6
      Fireballs = 126, half if save)... but over the long haul, I'm not sure you'd be better
      off...<br>
      <br>
      So here's the question... (and this will be interesting to see AFTER people have played BG
      as well). What is the ALL-AROUND best party for what people foresee as being the skills
      necessary to be successful in BG? (Oh and watch class/race/alignment constraints - none of
      this Paladins cruising around with Druids stuff... might be ok for a short time, but
      Paladins and Druids would each find the experience 'unpalatable' after a while...) </font></small></p>
    </blockquote>
    <p><small>He then looks at Racial class limitations...</p>
    </small><blockquote>
      <p align="left"><small><font color="#8080C0" face="Bookman Old Style">The only race that
      comes close to having a level limit in BG would be halfling clerics, who would normally be
      capped at level 8. With the experience point cap of 89,000 this will not be an issue
      (since you can only reach level 7 as a single-classed cleric).<br>
      <br>
      We have NOT decided how we are going to handle this in expansions.</font></small></p>
    </blockquote>
    <p><small>Then a look a the new beta testing going on at Black Isle Studios...</p>
    </small><blockquote>
      <p align="left"><small><font color="#8080C0" face="Bookman Old Style">First, Black Isle is
      doing the testing... Bioware is just getting our input.<br>
      <br>
      Second, this additional testing is going to SPEED UP our ability to release the game. We
      are NOT holding the game for more testing, we are adding testers to get through the
      necessary testing faster.<br>
      <br>
      Third, I just like posting all my notes in threes (good luck you know) ;)</font></small></p>
    </blockquote>
    <p><small>And finally a look at the Paladin's detect evil ability...</p>
    </small><blockquote>
      <p align="left"><small><font color="#8080C0" face="Bookman Old Style">It will not run
      'automatically'.<br>
      <br>
      For purposes of game play, we assume that the Paladin in question has to stop and
      'concentrate' on whether he can detect evil in the area. He accesses the detect evil
      ability through his 'special abilities' icon - in many ways it is as if he stopped to cast
      a spell. We did not treat the spell EXACTLY like it is treated in AD&amp;D... instead of
      detecting evil acts (or evil intent) it will detect an overall inclination towards evil.
      Monsters will clearly emanate evil... characters with evil alignments will also emanate
      evil. Note that just because characters emanate evil does NOT mean that they are currently
      up to an evil act. Paladins would know just to be 'wary' of these characters - i.e. to
      keep an eye on them. Also, if a creature is emanating evil out of the line of site of the
      Paladin, the Paladin will detect the evil, but will not have a sense of where it is coming
      from (directionally).<br>
      <br>
      Finally, one last comment. If an evil character joins your party, you can automatically
      access his/her alignment (on the character information page) and KNOW that they are evil.
      However, any evil behaviors/tendencies will be buried in the scripts that control the
      character's behavior. They may be total law-abiding citizens while with your party (i.e.
      keeping a low profile), or they may not...</font></small></p>
    </blockquote>
